segments.text: This is all part of the interview format.
Good afternoon.
We're in the office of Marvin Townsend, city manager of Laredo, Texas.
Mr. Townsend is going to tell us about events in the history of planning in Corpus Christi during his years as city manager of Corpus Christi, Texas.
Mr. Townsend, I started out, as you say, making some assumptions about the role of planning in the management of the city.
Do you want to?
Well, I don't think you can identify and separate planning from the total staff responsibilities of the city.

So I don't think we can identify what is caused by planning versus what comes out of the engineering department or what comes out of the utility programs as they work on growth or the staff people responsible for transportation.
It's a team, which the planning responsibility is to focus on one part of it.
We're talking about a lot of years now.
Where do you want to start that process?
Well, why don't we start with your background and how you came to Corpus Christi and how you...
I know that you worked in the city and became the city manager.
I have a bachelor's degree in economics from Cornell University and a master's degree in public administration from Cornell.
The master's degree is with a city management major.
And I wasn't a minor, but I had a substantial number of planning courses, enough so that I could have gotten a master's in regional planning, except for an eight-hour design course.
So I have been actively involved in planning throughout my whole life.
I went to Corpus Christi in 1956 when I graduated from college.
And I was there until 1982.
I was the assistant city manager beginning in 68.
No, pardon me.
In 60.
And the city manager began in 68. Who was the city manager at the time that you were assistant city manager?
Herbert Whitney, who just died two days ago.
I had a telephone call.
I was trying to get straight.
It was about his death.
He was city manager from 58 until...
Well, 59 to 68.
Now, I guess all the prior city managers are deceased now, because Russian Leclerc, the one before that, has also passed away.
The city in 56 was about 100 and, let's see, let me work backwards.
I've forgotten exactly, but it was around 100,000 population.
And square miles was about 37 square miles.
During that process, it's grown by annexations and by physical growth to where it's now.
You've got the actual figures, I'm sure, but it's over 200 square miles of water and about 130, 140 square miles of water.
The area that is water is the Corpus Christi Bay.
And Uasis Bay.
And Uasis Bay.
And just down into the Gulf of Mexico from the city of Puerto Angeles down to the national seashore to protect for offshore drilling, to regulate offshore drilling.
So they go to Madre as well as Corpus Christi Bay as well as Uasis Bay.
OK.
So when you started working with the city, let's see, the comprehensive plan that was adopted by the city council was adopted around 53 or 54?
Yes, that was the Bartholomew study, yes.
And so where was the city government as far as implementing that when you joined?
Had it just about been built out?
It was a piece of work that was done.
in the 56th, and it left a very definite mark on the city, but it was basically just a planning document.
There are those, and I imagine the conversation with Mr. Anderson probably tied everything that happened to the city back to that Bartholomew plan.
Well, I don't find that to be true at all.
It was a growing city, and it is a growing city, and they've made accommodations step by step as the planning process has evolved.
But to give you an example of
The Harlan Bartholomew master plan called for expanding the present airport.
Instead, they built a new airport.
Well, there are those who think the plan was followed that says that that was all focused because the Bartholomew plan focused on it.
Well, obviously, the community was focusing on it, and I don't think that's really even the same solution.
Yes.
Thank you.
Yes, Louise.
OK, here we go again.
Well, there's no doubt that the expressway plan was a very major change.
But see, that wasn't in the Bartholomew plan in 53 and 54.
Well, yeah, because that was a response to things that occurred later.
I'm just trying to say, though, that to identify a master plan and say that it caused all these things or it was the major reason for all these things, it's just a step in the evolution of the city.
Well, what parts of the growth of the city do you think had to do with the comprehensive plan at the time that you were first working in the city?
Well, see, I'm not trying to suggest that having a plan is not an important part of the process.
And it's constant update.
But I mean, the 53 plan did not become the foundation stone for much of anything.
It became a point of departure for all these things.
It certainly did a good job in bringing things together.
Now, one thing it did do, for sure, it was the immediate catalyst to the correction of the railroad problem, which led to the construction of the harbor bridge and the Tule Lake lift bridge.

That was a very major change, and I think that probably was kicked off by the Area Development Committee's participation in that master plan report, because it set up a technical committee, and that technical committee involved people from the Navigation District, which was the port, and the county, and the city, and the railroads, and others.
And they did work carefully together to bring that very major change, which other things might not have followed had that not been true.
But even there, it was a major variation.
At one point, the plan talked about a tunnel, and it turned out to be a bridge.
These are rather substantial changes.
But I think it very clearly caused that to happen.
Now, the rest of it, there was underway reservoir studies then, and a dam was constructed shortly after the report was prepared.
But the studies that were ongoing for that dam were built into the report.
So it's the planning process.
It involves all of the departments, as well as planning as a coordinating vehicle.
Now, when Bill was there, Bill Anderson, he was the secretary to the technical committee, and he was right in the middle of these various actions.
And he was actively involved in the construction of the first reservoir, the expanded reservoir, Lake Corpus Christi.
Now, which one is Lake Corpus Christi?
OK.
It's the same reservoir that was the old lake, but a new dam was built, which is Wesley Seal Dam, in front of the old reservoir.
and flooded the old reservoir.
And the creation of the water district made that possible.
But see, when the water district was created then, that's the Lower Illinois Superior Water Supply District, it was larger than the city.
And today, it doesn't represent a third of the city, because it has not grown as the city's annexed and grown.
So the process of orderly growth, the process of having good subdivision regulations,
I think that's been a very important contribution to planning, is having subdivision regulations and then living with them.

I think that's been a very important part, that the subdivisions are basically laid out well, that there are arterial streets laid out, that there is a program of curb and gutter and sidewalks, and the city has gone into old areas and rebuilt them.
I was very much concerned to tie the reconstruction of the city and the planning of the city together.
I think historically too many planning departments have been

able to handle new growth and laying out subdivisions such as this, but really can't come to grips with the reconstruction of a city, housing programs, rehabilitation of old streets, and putting in utilities, and payment assessment programs, and the kind of hard work that you have to go through to rejuvenate an old neighborhood.
So you saw that there was not only planning for new growth in the city, but going back into the existing city and bringing it up to date.
And I, in fact, bought community development under planning about 1969 or 70.
There were ordinances for subdivision development in the city charter?
No, the charter is just a foundation stone.
The council has to adopt ordinances.
And those ordinances are adopted into law under the state platting law, which I believe is 964 , which says that whenever a piece of land is divided into two or more parts,
The person divided has to file a plat, and that plat has to comply with the city's ordinances.
And that plat must show the streets being laid out and the utilities being dedicated.
It must show how all of the services of the public are going to be provided, and you have to have access to it.

Well, most cities in Corpus Christi had an ordinance that went well beyond that and spelled out in great detail the construction standards and how you had to build sidewalks and you had to provide fibers under your acreage for parks and set up a lot of other requirements.
You had to put in sanitary sewers and storm sewers
When was that?
Oh, I think Bill Anderson was probably responsible for the first one, or the first comprehensive one.
I guess there was one even before that.
And I imagine that the first comprehensive platinum ordinance was probably adopted in the middle 50s.
Middle 50s?
OK.
They had one before that.
But I mean, I think the standards were brought up to far, or brought up to more acceptable levels in the middle 50s.
And was that ever updated?
Oh, yes.
Is that updated continually?
Yeah, that's right.
It's been changed a lot since then.
And what part of the, would that be part of the planning department?
Yeah, the planning department.
And what part, I realize that the planning department in Corpus Christi.
Oh, that's normally called current planning, but it was, back to the days we're talking about it, it was the planning department.
Right.
The old planning department was only, yeah.
Bill Anderson, Bob Burr, and I guess Earl Getz was there.
I guess there were about maybe five people, six people at most.
That was in the mid-50s?
Yeah.
Okay.
And so then...
At some time in the mid-60s, or 1974, maybe we're jumping ahead, but in 74, you reorganized the...
Offices of the city manager and the deputies.
Yes, yeah.
Well, there was once in 74 and once in 80 are the two dates that I've got.
So you were there.
Yeah, I guess that's correct.
What do you think?
Oh, I don't know.
The days kind of fall together.
You said 70?
74 was one date that I've got.
I guess that's right.
I guess I brought...
Yeah, we set up the Department of Planning and Urban Development in the 74.
That was probably right.
And included under planning community development and planning and something else.
I guess we separated current planning and long-range planning.
And then the change in 80, 81?
80, I think.
My date was 80.
Then we changed it, and we created a position of assistant city manager.
The assistant city manager took the place of the director of planning and urban development.
And under that assistant city manager, other functions were placed, which included park and recreation, which included the library, which included
I guess that's it.
And there are other city managers established, assistant city managers established at the same time.
So that basically we had everybody in the city reporting to either one of the three assistant city managers or to the deputy city manager or directly to me.
It was set up so eventually there would have been a fourth assistant city manager.
There isn't now.
It's presently operating with three assistant city managers.
One of those is now.
Well, the deputy manager is now Ernest Briones, who was the...
He didn't go through assistant city manager.
He moved up from director of planning and urban development to deputy manager.
What were you hoping to gain, improve, increase in terms of changing the organization or developing the organization even more?
Well, there's two changes in that process.

One was the matter of the city manager's span of control being much too large, having some, I guess, 18 people, probably 20 people, no, I guess 18, something like that, reporting directly to the city manager.
The other, the earlier change, bringing community development and planning together, was to make more realistic current planning.
Here you had the community development program, which I forgot now what the money was, but $3 or $4 million a year.
That process of planning really wasn't even tied in with the so-called physical planning of the city.
And the planners really weren't very practical people in terms of making things happen.
And I felt that that tie needed to be made.
We needed to relate housing and zoning to what's happening out on the street.
It doesn't do any good to be concerned about the zoning and not be concerned about the condition of the housing, or the trash on the street, or the abandoned cars living on property.
Just because the book says the zoning is right doesn't mean that the living conditions have been corrected.
It's all got to be tied together.
And so I felt that the current planning needed to be tied into the community development planning, that it had to be all the same process.
I think that's always been my concern about planners generally is that they don't seem to understand that a plan is no good unless you carry it out.
Right, the implementation.
When you can't carry it out, it's in a planning department someplace.
You've got to mix with the operating people and revise the plans to be realistic and then carry them out.
If they don't get carried out, they don't do any good.
And that's still basically the problem.
For somebody to sit around and draw up goals programs or draw up plans or draw up master plans without the ability to implement those plans and without the organizational ability is just hot air.
Okay.
What are some of the things that you feel were implemented that were most important to the growth of Corpus Christi?
Say, when you first went in as assistant city manager, start there.
I mean, the things that
We know that Bill left off about the highways and the transportation and the port.
I guess whatever you saw is important because, right, a plan is a piece of paper, but what was the implementation that really affected the purpose?

For a long while, three of the things that were very important to us was a long-term water supply, which we accomplished with the construction of Choke Canyon, if it ever rains in that part of the country.
Well, it sure hasn't in a while.
The reservoir is almost empty.
120 million dollars worth of reservoir.
And a second big...
A need was the need to build a convention facility so that the city could more actively enter into the convention business, which we accomplished on the Bayfront, finally, after several false starts.
Another was the development of Crookston Beach.
which have been allowed to become almost a slum.
Several hurricanes and a lot of hard work.
We got cleaned up pretty much.
And we plan to go for it now.
It's pretty much... Is that North Beach or the beach in front of the Coliseum?
North Beach.
Okay, North Beach.
But that's called Cochise Beach.
That's the correct name for it.
South Beach is called E Beach.
I think we accomplished...
Looking back, the development of Ocean Drive was a major project during that period of time.
What kind of street should it be, and the fact that we decided to have a median, and the fact that we developed some big parks simultaneously to it.
See, for instance, Cole Park and Swanton Park, those didn't exist.
We pushed the seawall out in the water and then filled in behind them, along the part of the street, technically.
Those two parks were built as part of the street.
They had a seawall someplace, so we said, why not put it out in the water?
get as much material as we can.
In fact, we dredged in behind coal and we dredged in behind slander as well as hauling a lot of material.
Right.
I remember Coal Park prior to the ocean drive.
It's just that little block that used to fall off.
Yeah, yeah.
Well now, that was solely a city program?
Was it at all involved in...
Preserving the open space.
We got federal funds to buy the open space.
It's always intrigued me.
We had to back off a couple pieces, because they were partially developed out in the water.
They were also owned by some very influential people.
But I think the main reason was that they were partly developed.
There was improvements on the water side.
Mrs. Sam Wilson, right there at the Doddridge or Weber and the Ocean Drive.
Yeah.
So owned by somebody else now.
properties, which are out there right by Sauna Park.
Just before you get to it, there's two or four houses enrolled.
You got some finger piers down there.
And a house that's become.

a lot of controversy here up here of late that one house that's on the water side after you passed the Baptist Church yeah yeah Mr. Henry Stewart owned it and that was taken out of the project and even then we just got to approve about four to three votes uh by city council yeah now if you go back and ask those councilmen about that project all think it's wonderful nobody remembers voting against it well what were some of their uh objections well buying
buying the last piece of waterfront available for private development, and that people who bought those lots ought to be able to develop them, et cetera.
See, the statement in bought, for what today is peanuts, I think the whole project wasn't over, I've forgotten the figure, but I think it was over $400,000, $500,000.
Bought.
That's amazing.
Every strip of land that was as much as 1,000 foot in a row,
And that's how Doddridge Park, the city had a little piece of land at Doddridge Park, but expanded to Doddridge Park or wherever.
Expanded, bought Swantler Park.
Swantler was one of these places like Cole Park where it just fell off right at the edge of the road.
And bought that whole strip from the Baptist Church in the town.
Now some of it had to be bought because the old Ocean Drive was so narrow that in putting down the new Ocean Drive, it had to have some support.
And so the tracks had to be purchased because there was such a large portion of them being purchased anyway that we felt, why not buy the whole thing?
But we did successfully carry that out and that certainly has had a big impact.
Obviously the sewer plants had to be planned and built.
And that worked quite well, even though now it's become quite a problem, because it had some monumental problems with some of the contractors.
And that sewer plant is located?
Sewer plants, they're all over it.
OK, I'm familiar with one over by Cuyahoga.
Yeah, it's called Cuyahoga.
That's the largest now.
But the Broadway, what was the largest, which is right downtown on the edge of the ship channel, the west side is on Saratoga and Greenwood.
And then there's the Allison plants out by West Goose Park out in Annabelle.
Right.
And there's two on the far above.
There's one on Padre Island.
So all those have developed.
In 56, there were two sewer plants.
When was the decision to go ahead and, or was there a time when there was a decision to go ahead
and add new sewer plants into the city growth?
Well, throughout the whole process.
Like I say, the one out of Saratoga, which was the third sewer plant built, called the Westside, was built in the 50s, 60s, 60s.
We had one along through there.
And the fourth one was the Allison plant out by Westwood Park.
And then the fifth and sixth ones were at Florida Bluff.
And the seventh out of Allen.
Annexation has been a very important part of Corpus Christi.
Were it not for annexation, it would be just a new city with much better traffic right now.
And that started back in 54 when they had the first, well really,
I think Billy Anderson went to Corpus Christi to, one of the purposes was to straighten out the boundaries, in other words, to carry out the first annexation there.
I don't mean the first, but there was a substantial annexation in 54 and 55.
And then we carried out a big one in 61, and that's when Flower Bluff was annexed, and then Count Allen and H. Willis Midway was annexed.
And that caused a lot of grief.
Where did he live there?
Up until 70.
OK.
I'm sure you've heard a lot about the .
And then, because those were so large, then there were just a bunch of filling annexations for the next decade.

But of course, now the annexations are gradually going forward until they include a substantial part of Padre Island now, mostly developed area of Padre Island inside the city, as well as the area out the Orangeville Highway, which is out west of Calhoun.
Right.
When did the annexation start?
at Padre Island beginning in the 70s or late?
Well, Flora Bluff was annexed in 61.
OK, Flora Bluff.
Was annexed in 61.
And then the causeway was annexed as part of Laguna Madre.
You see, the whole of Laguna Madre was annexed to control oil and gas exploration.
It would require storm shoulders.
It would require spacing so that the would be too close together.
It would require that the platform be a certain distance off the shore and such as this.
And then the first Padre Island annexation happened in the 80s.
So that's been very recent.
Yeah.
That's just about .
We were having a public meeting .
OK.
Same with the Orange Grove Highway.
Now, you understand what I mean by that?
You know where Calhoun is?
Yeah.
Well, this is on west of Calhoun.
Right.
Yeah.
As a matter of fact, I just drove that highway yesterday.
Coming here?
Yeah, coming in this way.
Okay, that's not the fastest way.
That's all right.
Where are you coming from?
Well, I was coming from College Station.
Oh, all right.
Well, I always take a different route.
That's okay.
So I went through Tynan and Orange Grove on towards Alice.
And the Orange Grove Highway is 181?
No.
Coming into Corpus Christi?
No, that's the beach highway.
Okay.
Yeah.
Thank you.
Carlos?
Okay, where were we?

Well, I want to ask you about, you talked about the reconstruction in the internal part of the city, and I want to ask you about the attitudes towards urban renewal in Corpus Christi, because I understood that there weren't any federal urban renewal.
Yeah, urban renewal kind of was an idea whose time came and went.
Now, how it would have changed the city, had the city taken advantage of it,
I don't know, looking back, I mean, maybe we would have gotten some neighborhoods restored earlier.
The big problem with urban renewal was clearance.
And who knows now what would have happened if the election in 1959 had passed.
I've forgotten the date of the second election.
Which election was that?
Well, the first urban renewal election was in 59.
In Corpus Christi?
Yes.
Okay, that was like...
A city-wide bond.
Right.
It failed, I think, four to one or something like that.
Well, no, in Texas, in order to have urban renewal, you had to have voter approval.
You had to take the concept, not the project, but the concept to the voters.
And then we went back to the voters again in 19, and I have to check the date.
I would guess 67, 8, 9, 6, someplace along there.
And it failed the
I guess the first one failed four and a half to one, and the second one failed four to one.
It was enough so that I said to my wife, at this rate, we have to have nine more elections before it'll pass.
It was the kind of thing where all the so-called good guys in town were in favor of it, the Chamber of Commerce, all the civic clubs, but it still failed that badly.
Of course, the reason was that you can't pass something on a concept.
I remember one old man, I talked to him for an hour, but he'd been given a map by the opposition
And the map was the map of the area of substandard housing.
He'd been told in that meeting by the opposition that if your house was in the gray area, it went.
Clearance, total clearance.
And even though this guy had a lot of respect for me, and we talked for an hour, at the end he said, but Marvin, my house is in the gray area.
And that was the story of urban renewal in Purpose 50.
To me, that one little comment just tells it all.
I mean, it never passed because the lies were so easy to make and the program based upon philosophy could never pass.
What did you say the advantages would have been to the city?

Well, like the project that was the first proposed project took the oldest part of the city in a very rundown park called the, some called it the Cut, basically the area between the expressway and the Broadway and
adjacent to the sewer plant and back over to Port Avenue.
Right.
And converted that into a complete redevelopment area.
Now, what do you need, Bob?
I just wanted to know, are we playing games with the court tomorrow?
Tax cases?
Gosh, I don't know.
What cases are set tomorrow?
I thought you might know.
I'll call one of the lawyers and ask them.
Flo should be around.
Is he in the tax office?
I haven't checked.
Oh.
I always love the Uber.
OK. That's fine.
OK. Ah, where was I?
OK, so the first project for urban renewal was proposed for that area, between Rob and I. Yeah, in what later became the Coles High Alco area.
And I don't know what would happen if it had been approved.
The concept was almost total clearance.
It was going to be redeveloped with some apartments and some single family housing around the cemetery and some existing churches.
They're still now, 25 years later, working in that same neighborhood with CD money.
And finally got, well, I haven't been back, but I think all the streets are now reconstructed.
And there's still some pretty bad slums in that neighborhood, though.
And after a renewal went down the second time, a 221 project, which is a housing project owned by a nonprofit corporation, but still basically, well, it's
A lot of people have Section 8 housing assistance grants to let them live there.

But they went in with the city's cooperation that bought the worst four blocks in the slums and built a cooperative project with the St. Matthew's Baptist Church acting as one of the key sponsors for it.
So I don't know whether it would have changed dramatically.
I'm sure that those kind of things would have happened a lot faster with urban renewal because it would have been a get in, get out kind of thing.

I know that some of the projects now where they're working on the city hall site, for instance, and the courthouse site, those tracks might well have been bought and cleared quickly with urban renewal, and maybe those improvements could have been built ten years ago.
That's what would have happened there, and maybe the city hall and courthouse would be being built someplace else.
I don't particularly agree with where the city hall is being built.
In fact, I think it's wrong.
So it's who knows what the right solution would have been.
But all of those things evolve as the city grows, and there's no one process.
To me, the process of planning is to be at the front in that
evolving and to see that in fact as much information as is possible goes into the process and not a bunch of off-the-cuff opinions.
A lot of planners think that because they're a planner they can make some grandiose comment about something and it's supposed to be good because they say it's good.
And if they can't support what they're saying then their views are no different than the man on the street.
The planner's got to be prepared and put hard, logical reasoning behind what he says, and then help that department head carry it out.
Right.
So one of your major concerns is how do you get a plan off the paper into the actual construction?
Yeah, and the actual construction, and the other way around, too.
Thank you, ma'am.
Well, how did the city approach the reconstruction then in the older parts?
Was there a plan?
I mean, in a plan, what was the method for approaching that reconstruction?
Well, the difference between urban renewal and non-urban renewal is the difference between massive reuse of land versus rehabilitation of existing uses.
Urban renewal lets you go in and clear so you can rearrange street patterns.
And you could regroup the properties.
You didn't have to accept the subdivisions as they were laid out.
You could start over again.
So without that, you have to go about it the other way.
You have to go in and rehabilitate it as it sits.
So there are still some land use problems in Corpus Christi that will never be solved by current techniques.
There's a little subdivision off of Port Avenue called Industrial Boulevard.
There's another one that's, I've forgotten the name of it, but it runs off of the port at the curb, runs back toward Agnes, where you have a tough mix of industrial uses and single-family houses.

It's surrounded by a cement plant, or it was a cement plant on one side, I think it's probably vacant now, railroad track at the other side, and a great big cotton compress on the third side, and Port Avenue on the fourth side.
It's only three lots deep, and four lots deep maybe, and
probably have 200 lots in all together.
That is a tough land use problem that all the rehabilitation money in the world will probably never really solve.
At some time, maybe the private uses will buy it out and turn it into all industry.
But right now, it's home for a lot of people, and they've lived there for years, and yet there's slums.
So that's the kind of land use problem that without the tools of urban renewal, it's kind of hard to solve.
But many other subdivisions have been solved very nicely.
Molina, behind the golf center, was a slum partly because of the influence of Cliff Moss Airfield, which was the old airport, and partly because it was a poor neighborhood in a very poor area.
It was kind of a poor school district that was largely controlled by the farmers and the ranchers.
Do you know where Molina was?
Do you know where Horn Road is?
Yeah.
Well, Horn Road is now between the Golf Center and Molina.
It used to be between the airport and Molina.
But Molina in 56 had some dirt roads, no curb and gutter, standing ditches, no drainage, no sewer.
So it was little two inch water lines or even smaller.
And the city went in there and
completely redid that subdivision.

Built big storm sewers, big open concrete channels that run all the way to Oso Creek to drain it, and then put in sanitary sewers that ran down to the sewer plant I was telling you about before, the west side plant, and then went in with the two basics done underground, went in and replaced the water lines and replaced the gas lines and put in pavement with curb and gutter, and went in at the same time with what's called concentrated code enforcement,
where HUD loans were available as well as city loans to rehabilitate the houses and get rid of the privies and connect the people to city sewer as well as improve their houses.
So it was a combined effort, and it's been quite successful.

If you look at Molina now, it's nowhere near, it's still not probably not the place you'd pick to live, but I mean it's basically a subdivision of controlled land use, and most of the houses are now up to standard.
And that's not just, I'm picking Molina, but it was true in Gardendale.
You know Gardendale?
Probably.
I'm not sure.
Gardendale went from Staples to Everhart.
Okay, yeah.
The roads are...
Betty Jean, and Nelson, and Burton, and Williams Drive.
Anyway, they run it from the railroad track back to Blanche Moore's property.
You know that big track on Padre Island Drive that's undeveloped from Everhart to Staples?
And Blanche Moore's school sits on the other side of it?
Well, that's Gardendale.
That whole side of it is back there.
Around the 50s, Gardenville had no sewer, had little two-inch water lines, had open ditches on both sides of the streets.
Some of the streets were in very bad shape, had bad gas lines, very huge stop signs, very huge street lights.
And Reed did the whole subject.
Got the property owners to participate on the sewer lines and make connections to the sewer system.
And Gardendale is now almost a standard subdivision.

In fact, of course, there was other factors involved with Gardendale, because you had tremendously expensive improvements around it, which just kind of made those big lots in Gardendale also quite advantageous for the person that wanted some space, but couldn't afford to buy a big lot in Country Club.
So all those things were happening, and I think that basically through the 50s and 60s,
the 60s maybe, and the 70s, the city got rid of many, many, many problems that had existed in the World War II development.
